<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2005-04-04a.78.11" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/lord/100298" speakername="Baroness Hollis of Heigham" colon=":" colnum="78"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds05/text/50404w03.htm#50404w03_spmin3">
	<p pid="a.78.11/1">No such study has been undertaken. It is for individual countries to develop policies and laws to protect the interests of members of private and occupational pension schemes, although the Occupational Pensions Regulatory Authority (OPRA) has cases where it is dealing with parent companies abroad.</p>
	<p pid="a.78.11/2">In cases where the parent company is domiciled outside the UK and the UK company is unable or unwilling to stand behind its pension promises, OPRA&mdash;from <phrase class="date" code="2005-04-06">6 April 2005</phrase>, the Pensions Regulator&mdash;will engage with the parent company and, where appropriate, exercise powers to try and protect the pension scheme.</p>
	<p pid="a.78.11/3">It is expected that most companies want to stand behind their pension obligations. The EU directive on the activities and supervision of institutions for occupational retirement provision (directive 2003/41/EC) will provide a common framework of protection across EU member states.</p>
</reply>
